Subject: use epoll_pwait so Android x86_64 does not SIGSYS

Applies to: tailscale 0.7.1 (pub.dev), github.com/danReynolds/tailscale_dart
Tracked by: aer-works/aer-flow#303
Apply with: pixi run mobile-patch

Aer.Mobile dies on startup on any x86_64 Android emulator, before Flutter renders:

    F libc  : Fatal signal 31 (SIGSYS), code 1 (SYS_SECCOMP), syscall 232
    F DEBUG : Cause: seccomp prevented call to disallowed x86_64 system call 232

Syscall 232 on x86_64 is epoll_wait, which Android's seccomp filter denies for app
processes. The package's Go shim calls it via unix.EpollWait. lib/main.dart calls
TailnetGateway.init() before runApp(), so the Go runtime starts first and the process
is killed with no UI shown.

Why arm64 was unaffected: arm64 Linux has no epoll_wait syscall at all, so x/sys maps
EpollWait onto SYS_EPOLL_PWAIT there. Compare, in golang.org/x/sys/unix:

    syscall_linux_amd64.go:9   //sys EpollWait(...)
    syscall_linux_arm64.go:11  //sys EpollWait(...) = SYS_EPOLL_PWAIT

So real arm64 devices already take the epoll_pwait path. Only x86_64 -- emulators and
most CI runners -- hits the blocked syscall.

x/sys exports no EpollPwait wrapper (only EpollCreate, EpollCtl, EpollWait), so the fix
issues the syscall directly, mirroring the call form x/sys itself generates for arm64.
The trailing 0, 0 is a nil sigmask and zero sigsetsize -- the kernel skips the sigmask
entirely when it is NULL, making this semantically identical to EpollWait. SYS_EPOLL_PWAIT
is defined on both amd64 and arm64, and the patched file gofmt-checks clean and typechecks
under GOOS=linux for both GOARCH=amd64 and GOARCH=arm64.

Retire this patch once upstream ships the fix and we take the release. If it stops
applying, upstream has touched this code -- check whether it is fixed rather than
force-fixing the patch.

diff --git go/reactor_linux.go go/reactor_linux.go
--- go/reactor_linux.go
+++ go/reactor_linux.go
@@ -5,6 +5,7 @@ package tailscale
 import (
 	"encoding/binary"
 	"fmt"
+	"unsafe"

 	"golang.org/x/sys/unix"
 )
@@ -105,12 +106,35 @@ func (p *epollReactorPoller) Unregister(fd int) error {
 	return nil
 }

+// epollPwait issues epoll_pwait rather than epoll_wait.
+//
+// unix.EpollWait maps to SYS_EPOLL_WAIT on linux/amd64, which Android's seccomp filter denies
+// for app processes: an x86_64 emulator is killed with SIGSYS (syscall 232) before any UI
+// renders. arm64 Linux has no epoll_wait syscall at all, so x/sys already maps EpollWait to
+// SYS_EPOLL_PWAIT there (syscall_linux_arm64.go), which is why real arm64 devices are
+// unaffected and this went unnoticed.
+//
+// x/sys exports no EpollPwait wrapper, so this mirrors the call form it generates for arm64
+// verbatim. A nil sigmask (the trailing 0, 0) makes it semantically identical to EpollWait.
+func epollPwait(epfd int, events []unix.EpollEvent, msec int) (int, error) {
+	var zero byte
+	p := unsafe.Pointer(&zero)
+	if len(events) > 0 {
+		p = unsafe.Pointer(&events[0])
+	}
+	r0, _, e1 := unix.Syscall6(unix.SYS_EPOLL_PWAIT, uintptr(epfd), uintptr(p), uintptr(len(events)), uintptr(msec), 0, 0)
+	if e1 != 0 {
+		return int(r0), e1
+	}
+	return int(r0), nil
+}
+
 func (p *epollReactorPoller) Wait(out []ReactorEvent, timeoutMillis int) (int, error) {
 	if cap(p.scratch) < len(out) {
 		p.scratch = make([]unix.EpollEvent, len(out))
 	}
 	events := p.scratch[:len(out)]
-	n, err := unix.EpollWait(p.epfd, events, timeoutMillis)
+	n, err := epollPwait(p.epfd, events, timeoutMillis)
 	if err != nil {
 		if err == unix.EINTR {
 			return 0, nil
